      <title>Refactoring Legacy Code</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/talks/refactoring-legacy-code/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 25 Nov 2024 15:00:26 -0900</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/talks/refactoring-legacy-code/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;refactoring-legacy-code&#34; class=&#34;heading&#34;&gt;Refactoring Legacy Code&lt;a href=&#34;#refactoring-legacy-code&#34; aria-labelledby=&#34;refactoring-legacy-code&#34;&gt;&#xA;&lt;!-- &lt;i class=&#34;fas fa-link anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/i&gt; --&gt;&#xA;        &lt;svg class=&#34;svg-inline--fa fas fa-link anchor&#34; fill=&#34;currentColor&#34; aria-hidden=&#34;true&#34; role=&#34;img&#34; viewBox=&#34;0 0 640 512&#34;&gt;&lt;use href=&#34;#fas-link&#34;&gt;&lt;/use&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;&amp;nbsp;&#xA;    &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Legacy code can be a beast: fragile, complex, and often lacking the necessary tests to ensure changes don’t introduce&#xA;defects. But fear not! There are techniques you can use to effectively work with and extend it in a safe and effective&#xA;manner.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
